             attended upon us; though she says she never saw Mr. Sellers till Thursday night; Mr. Sellers slept with me on the Wednesday night, and Mr. Sellers upon the sofa in the drawing-room; and on Thursday afternoon, about two o'clock, Mr. and Mrs. Yates came down, for the first time, into the front parlour; about ten o'clock, and knowing that a bed lay there that they had taken from me, I thought to get it while they were out, for Mr. Yates had got three beds; I went up stairs and unlocked the door, for I had a key of the room, I unlocked the door, and asked Mr. Sellers to take it out of the room, nobody was present, the bed was taken out and the door locked again; towards seven o'clock in the evening Mr. Yates had a great many people<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="179609140033"></xptr>with him, somebody knocked at the door, I looked out, and it was a smith, Mr. Yates desired him to go up stairs and break open my bed-room door; Mr. Yates came up, and then he pushed me, and came with such force upon me as to throw me down, and then began to get the bed out.</p>
               <p>Mr. Yates dragged the bed out of the room, and threw it into the passage; 
               <persName id="t17960914-5-person137">
                  Mary
                   Thompson
               <interp inst="t17960914-5-person137" type="surname" value="Thompson"></interp>
